WEBVTT

00:05.939 --> 00:08.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good
evening. I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:08.442 --> 00:13.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight: The
U.S. ramps up its role in Syria,
putting special operations

00:13.714 --> 00:18.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
forces on the ground to bolster
the fight against ISIS.

00:18.285 --> 00:23.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then: a look at organized
labor's role in this year's race
for the White House.

00:23.490 --> 00:27.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON RALSTON, "Ralston Reports":
Withholding their endorsement, I
think they actually pushed

00:27.327 --> 00:30.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hillary into the position they
want on the so-called Cadillac
tax in Obamacare, which

00:30.731 --> 00:33.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they want repealed.

00:33.100 --> 00:37.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it's Friday.
Mark Shields and David Brooks
are here to analyze another

00:37.170 --> 00:39.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
full week of news.

00:39.806 --> 00:45.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
All that and more on
tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:45.178 --> 00:49.383 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

00:49.383 --> 01:01.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Shipwrecks off
the Greek islands claimed more
migrant lives today, 31 in all,

01:01.228 --> 01:05.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most of them children. That made
50 dead in three days, as the
weather worsens in the

01:05.299 --> 01:08.068 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Aegean Sea.

01:08.068 --> 01:13.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The deadliest incident today was
near the island of Kalymnos,
where 19 people drowned

01:13.807 --> 01:19.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trying to cross from Turkey.
Disturbing scenes were repeated
on Lesbos, where more bodies

01:19.579 --> 01:24.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
washed ashore, including several
babies and other children.
Volunteers helped remove them

01:24.618 --> 01:27.287 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for burials.

01:27.287 --> 01:31.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, in Athens, Greek
Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras
blasted Europe for its handling

01:31.925 --> 01:34.394 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the crisis.

01:34.394 --> 01:40.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALEXIS TSIPRAS, Greek Prime
Minister (through translator): I
want to say that, as a member

01:40.434 --> 01:44.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the European leadership, I
feel shame, shame both for the
inability of Europe to

01:44.905 --> 01:49.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
deal effectively with this human
drama, but also for the quality
of discussion.

01:49.176 --> 01:54.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In addition to
the dead, the Greek coast guard
said that it rescued nearly

01:54.247 --> 02:00.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
600 people in the last 24 hours.
Many of the migrants and
refugees have fled Syria,
Afghanistan,

02:00.120 --> 02:03.323 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Iraq.

02:03.323 --> 02:08.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Obama says he's ready
to sign a two-year federal
budget deal that won approval

02:08.028 --> 02:15.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the U.S. Senate early today.
It passed 64 to 35, in spite of
conservative opposition,

02:15.402 --> 02:21.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and just in time to avert a
federal default next week. The
package includes $80 billion

02:21.008 --> 02:25.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in new spending. It also
prevents a cut in Social
Security disability benefits and
a

02:25.679 --> 02:30.450 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
major hike in Medicare premiums.

02:30.450 --> 02:35.455 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the presidential campaign,
Democrat Hillary Clinton worked
to consolidate support among

02:35.455 --> 02:41.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
black voters in a swing across
the South. In Atlanta, she vowed
to end disparities between

02:41.328 --> 02:47.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crack and powder cocaine prison
sentences, and called for other
reforms.

02:47.067 --> 02:50.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate: As
president, I will work with
Congress to

02:50.737 --> 02:57.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pass legislation to ban racial
profiling by federal, state, and
local law enforcement.

02:57.577 --> 03:00.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

03:00.747 --> 03:03.216 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: It is
wrong, it is demeaning, and it
doesn't keep us safe or

03:03.216 --> 03:07.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
help solve crime. It's time for
us to put that practice behind
us.

03:07.421 --> 03:13.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Clinton also won
a key endorsement from New York
City Mayor Bill de Blasio.

03:13.393 --> 03:18.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Also today, the Republican
National Committee suspended its
partnership with NBC News for

03:18.532 --> 03:25.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a presidential primary debate in
February. GOP candidates
complained that CNBC moderators

03:25.739 --> 03:32.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
asked off-topic or -- quote --
"gotcha questions" during this
week's face-off in Colorado.

03:32.446 --> 03:38.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The last British detainee at
Guantanamo Bay has returned home
after being held for nearly

03:38.351 --> 03:45.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
14 years. Shaker Aamer is a
Saudi national who was married
to a British woman. He arrived

03:45.158 --> 03:49.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back in Britain on a private
plane, hours after being
released from the U.S. military

03:49.830 --> 03:55.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prison in Cuba. He was suspected
of links to al-Qaida, but never
charged. With Aamer's

03:55.869 --> 04:01.608 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
departure, 112 detainees
remain at Guantanamo.

04:01.608 --> 04:07.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New research is out that shows
breast cancer no longer strikes
black women less often than

04:07.481 --> 04:13.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whites. A study published this
week found the two races are now
diagnosed at the same

04:13.186 --> 04:19.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rate. That could be linked to
stepped-up screenings and higher
obesity rates in black
populations.

04:19.493 --> 04:24.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
At the same time,
African-American women are still
more likely to die of the
disease. The

04:24.231 --> 04:29.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
study appears in "C.A.," a
cancer journal for clinicians.

04:29.703 --> 04:36.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Stocks fell on Wall Street
today, but managed to post their
best monthly gain in four years.

04:36.009 --> 04:43.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Dow Jones industrial average
lost 92 points, to close at
17663. The Nasdaq fell more than

04:43.350 --> 04:47.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
20 points, and the S&amp;P 500
dropped 10. For the week, the
indexes were all up less than

04:47.821 --> 04:50.624 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a percent.

04:50.624 --> 04:56.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
American boots on the ground in
Syria; labor unions'

04:56.596 --> 05:14.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
waning influence on politics; a
tax increase threatens a Greek
speciality, and much more.

05:14.414 --> 05:19.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The United States steps up its
mission in Syria, part of a
coalition aimed at dismantling

05:19.819 --> 05:24.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Islamic State, as leaders
from the U.S., Russia and Iran
meet in Vienna trying to find

05:24.791 --> 05:28.795 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
a political end
to the civil war.

05:28.795 --> 05:32.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Confirmation that commandos are
going into Northern Syria came
at the day's White House

05:32.933 --> 05:34.501 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
briefing.

05:34.501 --> 05:36.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH EARNEST, White House Press
Secretary: The core of our
military strategy inside of

05:36.703 --> 05:39.973 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Syria is to build up the
capacity of local forces.

05:39.973 --> 05:44.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Spokesman Josh
Earnest gave few details on
whether the U.S. effort will

05:44.010 --> 05:47.948 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
aid Kurdish or Arab
fighters or both.

05:47.948 --> 05:52.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH EARNEST: The president did
make a decision to intensify
that support by offering a small

05:52.986 --> 05:59.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
number of U.S. special
operations military personnel to
offer them some advice and
assistance

05:59.192 --> 06:02.596 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on the ground as they
take the fight to ISIL.

06:02.596 --> 06:07.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That small
number, Earnest said, is fewer
than 50. And he insisted they

06:07.334 --> 06:10.537 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
will not be on a combat mission.

06:10.537 --> 06:16.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH EARNEST: The responsibility
that they have is not to lead
the charge to take a hill.

06:16.109 --> 06:19.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It still means that they're in a
dangerous situation. It still
means that they will have

06:19.846 --> 06:24.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all of the equipment that they
need to protect themselves if
necessary.

06:24.084 --> 06:30.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: U.S. special
operations troops have conducted
raids inside Syria, but this

06:30.924 --> 06:37.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will be their first sustained
presence. It comes amid Russia's
month-old air campaign

06:37.430 --> 06:44.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in support of Syrian President
Bashar al-Assad. And it marks a
shift for President Obama.

06:44.271 --> 06:48.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He had said repeatedly he
wouldn't commit ground troops in
Syria.

06:48.908 --> 06:54.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The military developments came
as Secretary of State John Kerry
was in Vienna for talks

06:54.748 --> 07:00.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on a diplomatic solution in
Syria. There was no agreement on
the future of Assad, but the

07:00.854 --> 07:06.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S., Russia and other nations
directed the U.N. to try again
to bring Syria's government

07:06.826 --> 07:09.929 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
and opposition
groups to the table.

07:09.929 --> 07:13.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KERRY, U.S. Secretary of
State: The United States
position is, there is no way
that President

07:13.833 --> 07:20.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Assad can unite and govern
Syria, and we believe that
Syrians deserve a different
choice. And

07:20.840 --> 07:31.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our goal is to work with Syria's
many factions to develop that
choice. But we can't allow

07:31.818 --> 07:37.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that difference to get in the
way of the possibility of
diplomacy to end the killing and
to find

07:37.157 --> 07:38.525 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the solution.

07:38.525 --> 07:43.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The ministers
will hold another round of talks
in two weeks.

07:43.763 --> 07:50.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, the killing in Syria
continued apace. Opposition
activists said a government

07:50.804 --> 07:58.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rocket barrage in a Damascus
suburb left at least 57 dead and
many more wounded.

07:58.845 --> 08:02.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We take a closer look at the
decision to send special
operations forces to Syria with
Greg

08:02.415 --> 08:05.719 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jaffe, who covers the Pentagon
for The Washington Post.

08:05.719 --> 08:09.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Greg, welcome back
to the program.

08:09.089 --> 08:12.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the White House is saying
that these special operations
forces are there to help what
they

08:12.359 --> 08:18.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
call moderates in the opposition
forces. What does that mean? Who
is that?

08:18.331 --> 08:22.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREG JAFFE, The Washington Post:
You know, it's primarily a
Kurdish group called the

08:22.102 --> 08:27.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YPG up north, along with some --
what they call the Syrian-Arab
coalition, which is a

08:27.407 --> 08:32.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coalition, sort of, of Arab
fighters who are fighting
alongside the Kurds up in the
north.

08:32.946 --> 08:38.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What's the
significance of singling out
those two groups to help them?

08:38.118 --> 08:42.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREG JAFFE: You know, I think
the first thing is, I think they
-- we feel like they share

08:42.756 --> 08:47.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our values or at least our
goals. They're sort of moderate
Syrian forces, and they have

08:47.727 --> 08:50.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shown some success.

08:50.096 --> 08:54.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think that's what the
administration is trying to
build on here. The YPG in
particular,

08:54.167 --> 08:58.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
backed by kind of American
airstrikes, has been able to
take back some ground from the

08:58.004 --> 09:02.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Islamic State. So, in a place
where they haven't seen a lot of
success, it's something.

09:02.776 --> 09:06.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, when they
say advice and assistance, which
is how the White House described

09:06.980 --> 09:10.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it, what does that mean? Exactly
what are they going to be doing
for them?

09:10.316 --> 09:15.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREG JAFFE: You know, the
Pentagon officials we spoke to
said that they primarily would

09:15.021 --> 09:18.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be at the headquarters level.
So, they won't be on the front
lines. They won't be calling

09:18.758 --> 09:21.594 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in airstrikes from what we call
sometimes first point of cover
and concealment. They

09:21.594 --> 09:24.798 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
will be further back than that.

09:24.798 --> 09:29.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think a big part of what
they do is assess the forces,
figure out what they need,

09:29.636 --> 09:35.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what equipment, weaponry the
U.S. can help provide them and
then also help them plan

09:35.041 --> 09:37.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the operation, make sure that
they have folks in the right
places, that they're
coordinating

09:37.811 --> 09:40.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as best as possible
with U.S. airpower.

09:40.547 --> 09:44.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So the mission
here is mainly anti-ISIS or
anti-Assad?

09:44.784 --> 09:51.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GREG JAFFE: No, it's anti-ISIS.
I think that's the complicating
factor of the Russians being

09:51.024 --> 09:54.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
involved as well, because I
think a lot of the forces that
we have worked with in the

09:54.961 --> 10:00.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
north are looking south to help
their brethren who feel kind of
battered by the Assad regime

10:00.033 --> 10:02.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and by Russia, but I think
that's a fight that we have
decided we don't want to pick

10:02.635 --> 10:04.771 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
right now.

10:04.771 --> 10:09.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Greg Jaffe,
we heard the White House
spokesman, Josh Earnest, say
this

10:09.542 --> 10:12.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is not a combat mission. He said
it's not a major departure from
what the U.S. has been

10:12.512 --> 10:14.948 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
doing.

10:14.948 --> 10:18.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How different is it from what
the U.S. has been doing? And
have there been covert
operations

10:18.084 --> 10:20.687 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
like this already going on?

10:20.687 --> 10:26.059 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
GREG JAFFE: Well, there
certainly have some been raids
that are covert. Have there been

10:26.059 --> 10:29.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
folks on the ground doing
advising and assisting on sort
of a long-term basis? Not that
we

10:29.762 --> 10:33.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
know of.

10:33.233 --> 10:37.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So it does seem like a
departure. Look, it's not a lot
of troops. I think it's less
than

10:37.770 --> 10:41.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
50. But, emotionally, it's a big
deal. We haven't had boots on
the ground in Syria before,

10:41.407 --> 10:43.309 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and now we do.

10:43.309 --> 10:46.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Greg Jaffe at The
Washington Post, we thank you.

10:46.079 --> 10:49.182 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
GREG JAFFE: Yes,
thanks for having me.

10:49.182 --> 10:53.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, just how
significant a move is this
decision to send these special

10:53.353 --> 10:59.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forces into Syria? And what
impact will it have on trying to
end the war diplomatically?

10:59.626 --> 11:05.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For that, we turn to former U.S.
Ambassador to Russia Michael
McFaul, and Joshua Landis.

11:05.732 --> 11:09.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's the director for Middle
East studies at the University
of Oklahoma.

11:09.168 --> 11:12.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we welcome you both
back to the program.

11:12.138 --> 11:14.774 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Ambassador McFaul, let
me start with you.

11:14.774 --> 11:21.548 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Before I ask about these
diplomatic talks in Vienna, what
effect do you think this
operation,

11:21.548 --> 11:25.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this announcement of putting
special operations forces into
Iraq is going to have on any
effort

11:25.652 --> 11:28.388 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to resolve Syria diplomatically?

11:28.388 --> 11:31.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL, Former U.S.
Ambassador to Russia: Well, I
think it will be in the margins,

11:31.824 --> 11:34.727 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but not a direct effect.

11:34.727 --> 11:40.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it really does have to
do with the desire by the Obama
administration to be more

11:40.066 --> 11:46.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
effective against ISIL. As
Secretary Kerry said today,
under Operation Inherent
Resolve,

11:46.172 --> 11:53.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they have now attacked -- they
have had 7,300 airstrikes, to
little effect. And now I think

11:53.046 --> 11:56.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they're doubling down, in
particular with the actors that
they think have been most

11:56.015 --> 11:59.218 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
effective before.

11:59.218 --> 12:04.924 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But it was a station
identification for our Russian
interlocutors and for everybody
else

12:04.924 --> 12:09.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we are involved in Syria
and that our people and our
partners in Syria have to be

12:09.195 --> 12:12.231 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
part of a negotiated process.

12:12.231 --> 12:17.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Joshua Landis,
how do you see this move by the
U.S. to put less than 50

12:17.070 --> 12:20.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
special operations troops in? Is
it going to have an effect on
resolving what's going

12:20.640 --> 12:22.775 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on in Syria?

12:22.775 --> 12:25.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA LANDIS, University of
Oklahoma: It's not going to
resolve anything. It's going

12:25.545 --> 12:31.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to have a slight effect, but
America is saying that we're
here.

12:31.217 --> 12:37.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They have had a lot of
criticism, President Obama's had
a lot of criticism, not only
internally,

12:37.023 --> 12:43.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because 50 intelligence people
said that his administration was
trying to gin up a success

12:43.396 --> 12:47.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
against ISIS, and it wasn't
having a success against ISIS.
So I think he's responding to

12:47.700 --> 12:52.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the internal criticism he's had
in the United States, but also
in the region.

12:52.438 --> 12:57.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Saudi Arabia and others are
saying Russia's moved into the
region because Obama's got

12:57.343 --> 13:01.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a very light footprint, and that
there's a power vacuum, and,
therefore, Russia is going

13:01.848 --> 13:04.984 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to come in and displace
the United States.

13:04.984 --> 13:10.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think he's trying to turn
up the heat a little bit without
getting America fundamentally

13:10.757 --> 13:16.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stuck in a third war in the
Middle East, because he's
discovered how difficult it is
to get

13:16.496 --> 13:22.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out of Iraq or Afghanistan, and
he doesn't want to leave the
next president with a real

13:22.101 --> 13:24.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
American presence in Syria.

13:24.704 --> 13:27.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So it's doing a little
bit, but not a lot.

13:27.874 --> 13:31.477 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, let me ask
you both separately then about
this meeting in Vienna wrapped

13:31.477 --> 13:36.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up today, two days. These were
representatives of 17 countries,
plus the U.N. and the E.U.

13:36.916 --> 13:42.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They basically came out with an
agreement, they said, to launch
a new peace effort involving

13:42.255 --> 13:45.892 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the Syrian government,
Syrian opposition groups.

13:45.892 --> 13:50.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do you read -- Ambassador
McFaul, how do you read what
they're saying in Vienna?

13:50.096 --> 13:54.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Well, first of
all, it's always good to talk,
it's always good to negotiate,

13:54.901 --> 13:59.272 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as opposed to not talking.

13:59.272 --> 14:04.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Second point, I think the hidden
news in the statement today was
that they said they're

14:04.143 --> 14:10.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to explore modalities for
a cease-fire, but not against
ISIS. And if they do that,

14:10.650 --> 14:17.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's a big objective, it's a
big success for the
administration, because, before,
the

14:17.290 --> 14:21.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russian forces were attacking
the folks that we were
supporting in Syria, and not
really

14:21.761 --> 14:26.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
attacking ISIL. So that would be
a breakthrough, in and of
itself.

14:26.032 --> 14:31.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But to your bigger question of
will this be a resolution, this
is just the start of what

14:31.604 --> 14:38.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would be a very long process. If
you saw the exchanges about
should Assad stay or go, we

14:38.111 --> 14:43.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were all reminded that we have a
long ways to go before you get a
process in place.

14:43.182 --> 14:47.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was part of Geneva I and
Geneva II, the failed processes
before. I guess this is now

14:47.587 --> 14:53.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Vienna I. And, you know, I'm
skeptical that it will be easy
to do, but I applaud the efforts

14:53.559 --> 14:55.528 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for trying.

14:55.528 --> 15:00.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Joshua Landis, do
you see -- getting back to what
the ambassador said a moment

15:00.199 --> 15:03.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ago, do you see this as a
potential breakthrough in here
somewhere in dealing with Assad,
President

15:03.603 --> 15:05.404 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Assad?

15:05.404 --> 15:10.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA LANDIS: Well, like the
ambassador said, the two sides
are worlds apart.

15:10.510 --> 15:14.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What they do agree on is that
there has to be a political
solution. What the Russians

15:14.914 --> 15:20.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Assad believe a political
solution is that, essentially,
Assad will conquer the

15:20.086 --> 15:25.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country, and they will kick out
the jihadists, and they will
have a political solution with

15:25.725 --> 15:30.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the more moderate militias by
bringing them back in from the
cold and having them accept

15:30.196 --> 15:34.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
an Assad regime again.

15:34.433 --> 15:40.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
America, of course, sees a
political solution as Assad
stepping down, having regime
change

15:40.072 --> 15:47.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that will bring eventually a
semi-ascendancy to Syria. And
those -- the two sides couldn't

15:47.246 --> 15:52.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
farther apart on this. So, I
don't think we're going to see a
resolution any time soon.

15:52.485 --> 15:57.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What will see is, in a sense,
the United States has said that
Russia is getting into a swamp

15:57.590 --> 16:04.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Syria. The big question is,
do they work for a cease-fire or
does America and its allies,

16:04.564 --> 16:09.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Turkey,
throw in more arms, TOW missiles
to fight the Russians and

16:09.602 --> 16:13.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
make sure that they
sink in that swamp?

16:13.005 --> 16:17.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Or do they not throw in those
weapons and allow Russia to
really dominate Eastern Syria

16:17.410 --> 16:20.980 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
-- Western Syria, excuse me.

16:20.980 --> 16:25.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Yes. There are
some real options there for the
parties to consider.

16:25.318 --> 16:30.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, Ambassador McFaul, where do
you see the U.S. going from
here? Do you see Ambassador

16:30.990 --> 16:36.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kerry -- I'm sorry -- Secretary
Kerry engaging, putting the U.S.
more on the line in Syria

16:36.495 --> 16:38.564 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in order to find a solution?

16:38.564 --> 16:42.468 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
MICHAEL MCFAUL:
Well, two things.

16:42.468 --> 16:47.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, I want to stress the
importance of this possible
cease-fire, because, before,

16:47.473 --> 16:51.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the Russian attacks were
primarily against moderate
Syrian groups that we were
supporting.

16:51.244 --> 16:53.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

16:53.179 --> 16:56.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: And we just
couldn't let that go on. We just
cannot allow the Russians to

16:56.716 --> 17:01.320 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
kill the people we're
supporting. So that could be an
achievement.

17:01.320 --> 17:05.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With respect to the second
thing, yes, Secretary Kerry,
he's going to fight for this.
He's

17:05.358 --> 17:10.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to be engaged. It's the
way he does business. And there
is no doubt in my mind

17:10.396 --> 17:13.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that if he sees even a glimmer
of hope, he's going to try to
get these parties together

17:13.633 --> 17:17.503 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and work towards a
political transition.

17:17.503 --> 17:21.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My heart's with him. My head
suggests that it's going to be a
long, difficult fight.

17:21.340 --> 17:23.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you both
seem to agree on that.

17:23.809 --> 17:28.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Joshua Landis, you both are
saying they're very far apart,
but there are some possibilities

17:28.381 --> 17:32.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here. What are the possibilities
that you see both sides working
on that could turn

17:32.084 --> 17:34.520 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
this into something positive?

17:34.520 --> 17:40.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA LANDIS: Well, it really
comes down to this -- these more
moderate militias that

17:40.159 --> 17:45.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are in the west of the country
that Assad wants to take. That's
Aleppo and it's Idlib.

17:45.598 --> 17:51.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Russia thinks -- and the
Syrians are all saying, you
know, people in Damascus are
telling

17:51.137 --> 17:53.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me, we're going to take Aleppo
in three months. Within a year,
you are going to see us mopping

17:53.072 --> 17:55.675 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
up in this area.

17:55.675 --> 17:59.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They think they're going to do
this. Now, it's quite clear,
from what the ambassador

17:59.345 --> 18:03.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said, that America is not going
to allow that to happen. If
they're really going to support

18:03.149 --> 18:07.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their allies in that region,
they're going to have to send in
more arms in order to scuttle

18:07.386 --> 18:11.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Russians' plans and to suck
them into the swamp, so that
they will come back in

18:11.057 --> 18:16.429 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a year's time on bended knee and
say, OK, let's talk cease-fire.

18:16.429 --> 18:20.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question of where that
cease-fire is going to be, what
lines are going to be drawn
between

18:20.933 --> 18:27.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
sort of Sunni Syria and
regime-dominated Syria is what
it's all about today. And that's
going

18:27.206 --> 18:30.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to -- a lot of that's going
to depend on military power.

18:30.343 --> 18:34.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Huge challenge,
and a lot of questions
remaining. And we thank you both

18:34.613 --> 18:37.650 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for helping us at least explore
this as it gets under way.

18:37.650 --> 18:39.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ambassador McFaul, Joshua
Landis, thank you.

18:39.885 --> 18:45.424 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
JOSHUA LANDIS:
Pleasure. Thank you.

18:45.424 --> 18:50.997 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Thank you.

18:50.997 --> 18:57.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now a look at
the power of organized labor in
politics.

18:57.169 --> 19:01.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Union membership is down, and
their influence is waning.

19:01.073 --> 19:06.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, as political director Lisa
Desjardins reports, Democrats
still vie for their
endorsements.

19:06.479 --> 19:09.582 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Welcome to
one of 2016's front lines.

19:09.582 --> 19:10.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PROTESTER: When I say
union, you say power.

19:10.916 --> 19:12.018 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PROTESTER: Union!

19:12.018 --> 19:13.152 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PROTESTERS: Power!

19:13.152 --> 19:14.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PROTESTER: Union!

19:14.253 --> 19:16.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PROTESTERS: Power!

19:16.922 --> 19:24.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: The complex
fight over unions. The drumbeat
was literal in Las Vegas
recently,

19:24.096 --> 19:28.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as the city's powerful Culinary
Union marched to the Trump
Hotel, which has blocked unions.

19:28.167 --> 19:30.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PROTESTERS: We are one!

19:30.903 --> 19:35.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: But this is
about more than Trump. It is
about union survival. In the

19:35.775 --> 19:41.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
nation as a whole, union
membership peaked long ago, in
1954, when more than one in
three

19:41.781 --> 19:48.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of all wage and salary workers
were union members. It declined
to 20 percent in 1983,

19:48.521 --> 19:51.290 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and then has kept sliding
down to 11.1 percent.

19:51.290 --> 19:53.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIA ELENA DURAZO, Union
Organizer: We're the only
organized force.

19:53.926 --> 19:57.630 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Longtime union
organizer Maria Elena Durazo.

19:57.630 --> 20:03.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIA ELENA DURAZO: I think,
unfortunately, unions have lost
so much strength and membership,

20:03.736 --> 20:08.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that our influence isn't what it
once was, but who else besides
unions fights for raising

20:08.574 --> 20:10.776 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the minimum wage?

20:10.776 --> 20:15.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: This is the
complex part. While unions
represent fewer voters, they

20:15.314 --> 20:19.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and their fight for wages
remain critical to Democrats.

20:19.785 --> 20:25.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
While some unions have made
endorsements of candidates, some
major ones have not yet.

20:25.057 --> 20:30.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those includes the Teamsters
with 1.4 million members and
also the AFL-CIO with 12.5
million

20:30.863 --> 20:35.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
members, both organizations
known for turning out voters.
And the expectation is, if they

20:35.401 --> 20:39.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
pick any candidate, it
will be a Democrat.

20:39.138 --> 20:42.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And those Democratic campaigns
are furiously fighting to get
their support.

20:42.508 --> 20:45.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
At that local rally
in Las Vegas...

20:45.277 --> 20:49.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate: I'm here
in support of Local 226.

20:49.248 --> 20:53.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: ... Hillary
Clinton made an unannounced
visit. Just a month earlier,

20:53.385 --> 20:59.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
her opponent Martin O'Malley
also stopped by a Culinary Union
protest. And Bernie Sanders,

20:59.492 --> 21:02.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he held a town hall with a
pivotal local chapter in March.
Why the contention?

21:02.995 --> 21:08.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON RALSTON, "Ralston Reports":
Culinary Union is by far the
biggest, most influential union,

21:08.234 --> 21:13.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
55,000 or so members, but, even
more importantly, the Culinary
Union is the Latino turnout
organization.

21:13.539 --> 21:18.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Jon Ralston,
veteran reporter and the host of
Nevada's premier political

21:18.244 --> 21:24.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
talk show, "The Ralston Report,"
says where unions are growing is
also where the Democratic

21:24.016 --> 21:28.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Party is growing, with Hispanic
workers. And Nevada's Culinary
Union is using that leverage

21:28.921 --> 21:31.390 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with candidates.

21:31.390 --> 21:34.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JON RALSTON: The Culinary is
doing something very smart, I
think. They've essentially --
withholding

21:34.994 --> 21:39.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their endorsement, I think they
actually pushed Hillary into the
position they want on the

21:39.165 --> 21:42.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so-called Cadillac tax in
Obamacare, which they want
repealed.

21:42.768 --> 21:48.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That so-called
Cadillac tax would tax extensive
and expensive insurance

21:48.707 --> 21:54.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plans that unions fought for. In
recent months, Clinton came out
against the tax. And in another

21:54.480 --> 21:59.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pro-union stance, she told Judy
Woodruff she opposes the
Trans-Pacific Partnership.

21:59.618 --> 22:03.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: Now
looking back on it, it doesn't
have the results we thought

22:03.389 --> 22:07.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it would have in terms of access
to the market, more exports, et
cetera.

22:07.793 --> 22:11.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Her opponent
Bernie Sanders, meantime, has
filed nearly a half-dozen bills

22:11.797 --> 22:16.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to help unions and has railed
against such trade deals.

22:16.135 --> 22:18.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (VT-I),
Presidential Candidate: These
trade agreements, among other
things,

22:18.204 --> 22:24.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have contributed to the fact
that we have lost almost 60,000
factories since 2001 and

22:24.877 --> 22:29.748 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
millions of decent-paying jobs.
And I think enough is enough.

22:29.748 --> 22:33.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: But while
Democrats hope for union
support, some key union leaders

22:33.419 --> 22:35.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have questions for them.

22:35.988 --> 22:41.026 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
J. David Cox is president of the
American Federation of
Government Employees. He watched

22:41.026 --> 22:44.697 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Democrats' debate in Las
Vegas and he noticed something.

22:44.697 --> 22:46.498 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
J. DAVID COX, President,
American Federation of
Government Employees: I heard
all five

22:46.498 --> 22:51.670 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the candidates on stage talk
about the need to raise wages in
this country. But the

22:51.670 --> 22:56.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one thing I didn't hear them
say was the word union.

