42:51.235 --> 42:55.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
available. However, the
country's former chief tax
inspector, Harry Theocharis, did
talk

42:55.540 --> 42:59.010 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to us, and was sympathetic
to the grape farmers.

42:59.010 --> 43:02.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARRY THEOCHARIS, Former Chief
Greek Tax Inspector: Any tax at
this point in time which is a
drag

43:02.046 --> 43:08.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on growth is a problem, because
Greece's problem is jobs. That's
our number one problem, and

43:08.019 --> 43:12.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we need to do anything in our
power in order to create more
investment and more jobs.

43:12.089 --> 43:16.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Do you think
that a tax like this will create
an incentive for a larger

43:16.360 --> 43:18.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
black market in this?

43:18.796 --> 43:23.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARRY THEOCHARIS: It's possible.
We already do have a big black
market, due to the way

43:23.868 --> 43:26.604 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that we license those
small producers.

43:26.604 --> 43:30.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How crucial is
this to the overall financial
health of the country?

43:30.875 --> 43:35.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARRY THEOCHARIS: This is a very
small, small issue. I think it
starts with the commission

43:35.980 --> 43:43.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
taking us to court in order to
have a level, fair playing
field, so this has nothing to

43:43.788 --> 43:48.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do with the actual austerity. It
is not a measure that is done
because of that.

43:48.893 --> 43:54.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And that last
answer gives hope to the people
of Tyrnavos. Under their

43:54.131 --> 43:59.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interpretation of European
rules, Greece can refuse to
implement the tax increase. They

43:59.871 --> 44:03.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just hope that, after giving in
to Europe over so many financial
issues, the government

44:03.641 --> 44:07.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Athens will be prepared
to fight for tsipouro.

44:07.078 --> 44:12.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANTONIS GIAMELIDES: That's our
tradition. That's our kind of
living, right? So, if we

44:12.683 --> 44:15.953 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
lose that, we're
losing everything.

44:15.953 --> 44:20.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In Greece,
tsipouro is known as the tear of
the land. But will this part

44:20.525 --> 44:25.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the land soon be in tears?
The key question for the
government is whether collecting
extra

44:25.763 --> 44:31.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
taxes makes good short-term
sense, or is bad for the economy
in the long term.

44:31.102 --> 44:42.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," Hari
Sreenivasan, Athens, Greece.

44:42.280 --> 44:52.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the second
part of our look at the
Affordable Care Act and health

44:52.089 --> 44:56.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
insurance coverage, as
year three gets under way.

44:56.427 --> 45:01.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This weekend marks the beginning
of open enrollment in the health
exchanges, and we're looking

45:01.365 --> 45:06.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at some of the questions about
costs and coverage. One
development this fall that's
turning into

45:06.370 --> 45:11.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a concern for some consumers, a
series of collapses of an
alternative to traditional

45:11.108 --> 45:15.346 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
insurance plans known as co-ops.

45:15.346 --> 45:18.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nearly a half of them, which
were created through the
Affordable Care Act, are now
shutting

45:18.516 --> 45:20.384 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
down.

45:20.384 --> 45:26.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I sat down to discuss this all
yesterday with Mary Agnes Carey
of Kaiser Health News.

45:26.424 --> 45:28.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And Mary Agnes Carey
is with us again.

45:28.392 --> 45:29.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, welcome back.

45:29.327 --> 45:31.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY, Kaiser
Health News: Thanks.

45:31.796 --> 45:37.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, let's focus
on these -- this thing called
co-ops. Remind us exactly what

45:37.134 --> 45:40.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they are. And what did the
administration want them to
accomplish?

45:40.671 --> 45:44.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: As they were
negotiating the Affordable Care
Act, Democrats wanted

45:44.508 --> 45:48.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a public option. They wanted a
uniform option available to
everyone across the country for

45:48.279 --> 45:51.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
health insurance. That
wasn't going to happen.

45:51.315 --> 45:55.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, as an alternative, they
created these independent,
nonprofit co-ops that were to

45:55.920 --> 46:00.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
be an alternative to the
traditional insurer. And it was
to be an option for consumers.

46:00.391 --> 46:04.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And they had --
they believed this was going to
cover a chunk of the uninsured

46:04.528 --> 46:05.363 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out there?

46:05.363 --> 46:07.565 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY:
They absolutely did.

46:07.565 --> 46:12.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But they ran into a few
roadblocks. For example, in a
budget deal a few years ago, the
funding

46:12.103 --> 46:15.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for co-ops was cut. There
recently was an announcement
from the Department of Health

46:15.840 --> 46:22.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Human Services they couldn't
give these companies and others
as much as anticipated

46:22.046 --> 46:24.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to help offset some of the
higher-cost cases. And that's
where some of the co-ops got
into

46:24.815 --> 46:26.784 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
trouble.

46:26.784 --> 46:31.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some of them were very popular.
They were low-cost alternatives.
That meant sometimes

46:31.389 --> 46:35.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sicker beneficiaries came to
them. And that's where some of
the financial problems happened.

46:35.359 --> 46:39.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let's look,
Mary Agnes, at a gentleman. He's
-- his name is Edward

46:39.797 --> 46:44.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Azria. He lives in New York. He
was in a co-op in Brooklyn, but
then it collapsed. Let's

46:44.902 --> 46:46.971 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
hear from him.

46:46.971 --> 46:50.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EDWARD AZRIA, New York Resident:
The premium and the deductibles
were good, certainly for

46:50.975 --> 46:55.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
my needs, because I'm not
habitually in the doctor's
office for anything.

46:55.513 --> 47:00.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so it was easy to maintain,
coming out and starting out on
my own, to take that monthly

47:00.151 --> 47:05.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
payment where it was, without
having it be too heavy of a
burden going forward. And they

47:05.189 --> 47:07.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
provided everything
that I needed.

47:07.358 --> 47:12.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My biggest worry is that, to
stay within the same price
point, if it's even going to be

47:12.129 --> 47:15.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
possible, is the level of
services going to be diminished
because they have to make up

47:15.866 --> 47:21.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for it? The price point of the
co-op was obviously too good to
be true.

47:21.105 --> 47:24.308 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, it is going to be
interesting to see what they
actually do come up with and if
they're

47:24.308 --> 47:27.545 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to cut the services
to make up for it.

47:27.545 --> 47:32.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Mary Agnes,
what does the administration do
for someone like Mr. Azria?

47:32.416 --> 47:36.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: HHS Secretary
Sylvia Burwell had a briefing
with reporters. She was asked

47:36.087 --> 47:38.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a few questions about the
co-ops. She said, they're going
to have special outreach to

47:38.589 --> 47:40.558 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
these folks.

47:40.558 --> 47:45.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're talking about 500,000
people or more in the 10 co-ops
that have folded that are

47:45.629 --> 47:50.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to be out there looking
for plans, reaching out to them,
explaining to them how to look,

47:50.067 --> 47:54.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how to navigate for their plans.
And also they're trying to
investigate what they might

47:54.739 --> 47:59.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be able to do, they being the
Department of Health and Human
Services, either
administratively

47:59.376 --> 48:03.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or through the legislative
process, to try to grant some
relief to some of these co-ops,

48:03.114 --> 48:06.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because of course there are some
that are still struggling
financially.

48:06.383 --> 48:10.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And do they think
they are going to be able to
find an option for someone

48:10.354 --> 48:12.123 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
like him at the
same price point?

48:12.123 --> 48:14.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY: I
think they could.

48:14.358 --> 48:18.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have to remember that, in
the Affordable Care Act, there
are different tiers of coverage,

48:18.195 --> 48:22.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bronze, silver, gold, and
platinum. If he's interested in
a lower monthly premium, a
bronze

48:22.833 --> 48:26.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plan might work for him. It may
not be the exact same plan he
had in his co-op, which

48:26.337 --> 48:29.273 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he obviously really liked.

48:29.273 --> 48:33.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, again, that's where,
whether you go on to
healthcare.gov yourself, or you
get assistance

48:33.644 --> 48:37.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from a broker or an insurance
agent, or work with many of the
community groups that are

48:37.882 --> 48:42.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind of on the ground trying to
help people find coverage, he's
going to have to get in

48:42.052 --> 48:47.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there and look, what's covered,
are my doctors covered, are my
prescription drugs covered,

48:47.291 --> 48:50.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how much does this plan cost in
the premium, in the
out-of-pocket costs, what's the
total

48:50.928 --> 48:53.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
package, and how does it compare
to what he had and what he can
afford?

48:53.998 --> 48:56.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Explain again,
Mary Agnes, why a number of
these co-ops just didn't make

48:56.700 --> 48:58.469 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

48:58.469 --> 49:03.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: They had
basically had solvency issues,
financial solvency issues.

49:03.274 --> 49:08.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they were the lower price
point, that tended to attract
sicker beneficiaries. That would

49:08.245 --> 49:12.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
drive up their costs. They had
anticipated fairly large
payments from the federal
government

49:12.850 --> 49:17.021 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to help offset the cost
of those sicker folks.

49:17.021 --> 49:22.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, of course, as we mentioned
earlier, there was a change and
their funding was cut early

49:22.193 --> 49:26.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on in inception of the co-ops.
And then, secondly, there was
another legislative change that

49:26.764 --> 49:30.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
adjusted the amount of money
that the federal government
could pay them.

49:30.501 --> 49:35.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a program that says, if you
have a lot of healthier
beneficiaries, you pay in, and

49:35.539 --> 49:37.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is the insurers pay in and
that money is distributed to the
insurance plans that

49:37.908 --> 49:40.945 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
take care of the sicker folks.

49:40.945 --> 49:44.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The insurers, including many of
these co-ops, expected a much
more generous payment from

49:44.949 --> 49:48.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the administration than they're
receiving. And that has hurt
their bottom line.

49:48.319 --> 49:51.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what can the
administration do to shore them
up, or can -- or is there

49:51.255 --> 49:53.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
-- are there options?

49:53.457 --> 49:56.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Well, for 10
of them at this point, they're
folding. They can't enroll

49:56.327 --> 50:00.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people in 2016. There are
23 co-ops. Ten are gone.

50:00.664 --> 50:05.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for the other 13, perhaps
the administration could do
something, whether it's through
their

50:05.236 --> 50:09.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
own administrative power or
through working with Congress,
because, remember, this is

50:09.373 --> 50:12.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
affecting people's constituents.
So, members of Congress are
hearing about this. There's

50:12.843 --> 50:15.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually two congressional
hearings that are going to
happen next week.

50:15.713 --> 50:19.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I expect there will be
greater focus on this, looking
at the co-ops that are still

50:19.149 --> 50:21.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
functioning and can
they help them.

50:21.652 --> 50:27.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, as we wrap
up, remind us again, when is
this third annual enrollment

50:27.157 --> 50:30.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
period coming up? And any other
advice for people who are
looking at whether or not they

50:30.561 --> 50:32.796 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
should sign up?

50:32.796 --> 50:35.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Open
enrollment starts November the
1st, but you can get on
healthcare.gov

50:35.933 --> 50:38.769 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
now and do some window shopping.

50:38.769 --> 50:44.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you want health insurance to
start January 1, you need to
enroll by December the 15th.

50:44.275 --> 50:47.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People always kind of forget
that. There is an administrative
period that needs to happen

50:47.411 --> 50:51.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get your coverage going. And
you can enroll through the end
of January.

50:51.515 --> 50:55.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, another piece of advice,
don't wait until the deadline.
Everyone -- we all love to wait

50:55.085 --> 50:56.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for the deadline,
but don't do that.

50:56.353 --> 50:57.655 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That's me.

50:57.655 --> 51:01.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Yes. Me, too.
I'm a reporter. That's what we
live by.

51:01.125 --> 51:04.461 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it would be important. If
you're interested in this, I
would encourage people to get on

51:04.461 --> 51:09.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
early and check it out. And if
you need in-person assistance,
get it. Look for a local
enrollment

51:09.366 --> 51:13.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
event. Call the 800 number on
healthcare.gov. Get the help
that you need.

51:13.103 --> 51:15.673 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So you can call
that number and get help?

51:15.673 --> 51:17.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: You can call
that number and get help.

51:17.708 --> 51:21.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They say they have -- they being
-- the Department of Health and
Human Services says they have

51:21.245 --> 51:25.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
improved the functionality of
not only the Web site, but to
make sure those lines, those

51:25.549 --> 51:28.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
toll-free lines, are answered
and that people know what
they're talking about.

51:28.319 --> 51:32.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mary Agnes Carey
with Kaiser Health News, getting
everybody ready for this

51:32.756 --> 51:36.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
third period of enrollment,
thank you very much.

51:36.427 --> 51:45.169 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY:
Sure. Thank you.

